// PushObjects pushes locally-materialized objects to the target.
//
// The receive-pack body (update-request header + pack) is written to a
// temp file before the POST, so the request goes out with an explicit
// Content-Length instead of Transfer-Encoding: chunked. Some servers
// — notably Cloudflare's git-over-HTTPS frontend — close the connection
// on chunked receive-pack uploads, matching upstream git's long-standing
// behaviour of buffering receive-pack bodies. Spooling also lets Go's
// transport retry transient connection failures via req.GetBody.
//
// The materialized strategy already requires the full source object
// closure to be local before encoding begins, so a temp file on upload
// doesn't change its fundamental shape. Relay paths (PushPack) keep
// streaming source bytes through to target with chunked encoding, and
// preserve the "streaming proxy" property git-sync is built around.

